{
  "doc_id": "40451",
  "text": "Previous extensive uranium mining in the ''Wismut'' region near Ronneburg (Thuringia, Germany) has enhanced environmental distribution of heavy metals and radionuclides. The compounds are considered to be hazardous based on what we know about their toxicity, but it is not known how environmental exposure to these compounds will affect human health. Several of the ''Wismut''-related compounds probably are toxic through formation of free radical oxygen species (ROS) [CITATION_1] , via irradiating mechanisms (radon) [CITATION_2] , or by interacting directly with cellular macromolecules (e.g., inhibition of DNA repair) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The release of radionuclides and uranyl compounds into the environment during uranium mining is associated with the transfer of these compounds into the food chain [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . The ingestion of contaminated soil or dust, moreover, increases the burden on the gastrointestinal system as well [CITATION_8] .",
